    <img src="http://www.stmgrts.org.uk/assets/images/2016/WINDRUSH_Windrush_1_thumb.jpg" width="150" height="100" alt="Windrush" align="right" style="border: 1px solid #ccc; padding: 1px;" />
<p>In the early hours of Tuesday June 22<sup>nd</sup> 1948 an 8,000 ton passenger ship, the <em>'Empire Windrush'</em>, slipped into Tilbury Docks and began to disembark nearly 500 Caribbean migrants. By some quirk of synchronicity this sociologically significant event &#8211; the beginning of mass migration into the UK &#8211; took place precisely 68 years before the people of the United Kingdom, concerned about the economy and immigration, prepared to vote on their place in the European Union.</p>

